{
  "texts": [
    "◁As is common in the modal logic literature (Chagrov andZakharyaschev 1997, Blackburn et al. 2001), we take a modal logic L for L(Φ, I) to be a subset of L(Φ, I) satisfying certain closure conditions.",
    "For familiar notation: if φ ∈ L, then ⊢ L φ; otherwise ⊬ L φ.Definition 1.2 (Classical Normal Modal Logic).",
    "L ⊆ L(Φ, I) is a classical normal modal logic iff for all φ, ψ ∈ L(Φ, I), i ∈ I:foot_7 1.",
    "Uniform Substitution -if ⊢ L φ and ψ is a substitution instance of φ, then ⊢ L ψ;2.",
    "Tautologies -if φ is a classical propositional tautology, then ⊢ L φ;3."
  ]
}